Short (one-line commit message) feat(auth): replace legacy user.repository with role-specific repos (customer/vendor/manager/admin)
Multi-line commit message (paste into git editor) Replace the legacy repositories/user.repository.ts with role-specific repositories: repositories/customers.repository.ts, repositories/vendors.repository.ts, repositories/managers.repository.ts, and repositories/admins.repository.ts.
Auth flows now route registration and login through the appropriate role-specific repository via services/auth.service.ts.
New services/customers.service.ts and example API route app/api/customers/[id]/route.ts.
Repositories reuse the existing users collection and enforce role filtering to avoid immediate DB migration.
The old repositories/user.repository.ts is retained until CI confirms all references have been updated and the build is green.
Testing / verification
Run type-check & build: npx tsc -p tsconfig.json --noEmit && npm run build
Start dev server and smoke-test GET /api/customers/<id>; ensure no password in response.
Search for leftover references: grep -Rn "user.repository" || true grep -Rn "userRepository" || true
Rollback
Revert commits that introduce role-specific repositories and restore previous services/auth.service.ts if build/tests fail.
Keep the legacy repositories/user.repository.ts until final removal commit after CI passes.
PR description (ready to paste) Summary
Replace the single user.repository pattern with four role-specific repositories to clarify domain responsibilities: customer, vendor, manager, and admin.
Update services/auth.service.ts to use role-aware creation and lookup.
Add services/customers.service.ts and GET app/api/customers/[id]/route.ts as an example consumer.
Why
Improves code clarity and prepares the codebase for role-specific business logic.
Avoids an immediate database migration by keeping a single users collection and enforcing role filtering at the repository level.
What changed
New files: repositories/customers.repository.ts, repositories/vendors.repository.ts, repositories/managers.repository.ts, repositories/admins.repository.ts, services/customers.service.ts, app/api/customers/[id]/route.ts.
Modified: services/auth.service.ts (now uses role-specific repos).
Legacy: repositories/user.repository.ts retained until CI/build is green.
How to test
Type-check & build: npx tsc -p tsconfig.json --noEmit && npm run build
Dev server: npm run dev
Smoke test: curl -i http://localhost:3000/api/customers/<id></id>
Rollback plan
Revert the refactor commits and restore repositories/user.repository.ts if any critical failures occur.
Release note / changelog entry Refactor: Split monolithic user repository into role-specific repositories (customer/vendor/manager/admin) and update authentication flows to use role-aware repositories. No DB schema changes — the users collection is reused with role filtering. CI must pass before removing legacy user.repository.ts.
Short PR/Slack summary (1-2 lines) Refactor: replaced legacy user.repository with role-specific repositories (customer/vendor/manager/admin) and updated services/auth.service.ts to be role-aware; added customers service and example GET API route. Legacy repo retained until CI passes.